<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06275084 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06275084 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  NEIGHBORHOOD; BEHAVIOR; GUIDELINE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  In her new book, &quot;Neighbor Law: Fences, Trees, Boundaries and Noise,&quot; Berkeleyattorney Cora Jordan suggests these steps in resolving a neighborhoodproblem:;   --Approach the neighbor cautiously and with a clear idea of whatyou'll say. Keep track of exactly when the trouble started. Communicate with&quot;respect and sensitivity.&quot; Don't call the police or complain behind aneighbor's back before trying to talk to them first. Assume they will bedefensive.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Living  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  DEALING WITH NEIGHBORS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  See also related story on this page.  </MEMO><TEXT>     --If that fails, the next step is to get a copy of the local noiseordinance that addresses your particular problem. Send a polite letter andenclose the ordinance. Keep a copy of the letter.;   --If that fails, and youlive in an apartment or condominium, bring in the landlord or report theproblem to the homeowners association. By now you should have a historyclearly documented. Wait for them to recommend your next move.;   --There'sstrength in numbers. If the neighbor is bothering you, there's a good chanceothers on the block have been bothered too.;   --If that fails, suggestmediation before calling the police or your attorney. Private and publiclyfunded mediators can be found in the yellow pages and through the courtsystem. Santa Clara County's program charges $25 for each disputing party.;  --hen things are resolved, bake a pie and take to your neighbor as a peaceoffering.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Donna Kato  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911001  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  230  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday, October 1, 199100275084,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>